Referring to the SRM of commercial aircrafts,1,2 the taper ratio of scarf repair was set to 1/30. The diameter of the repair region was calculated with the skin thickness and taper ratio. The general repair processes are shown as follows:


Use No. 240-grit or smaller abrasive paper to taper sand repair region at the ratio of 1/30. Milling equipment such as flexible disk sander or pad sander is involved in this step;

Lightly make the surface rough around the repair area with No. 180-grit abrasive paper;

Remove all dust in repair region with a vacuum cleaner, and clean the surface of repair with a cloth made moist with methyl isobutyl ketone or acetone;

Cut out a core repair plug from honeycomb core material and install the repair plug with core-splice adhesive. Make sure the core repair plug has the same shape and size as the core that was removed;

Cure the honeycomb core plug under standard process parameters;

Clean the repair surface, remove all dust with a vacuum cleaner;

Prepare and install the adhesive film and repair plies. Make sure the orientation and stacking sequence of repair plies were identical to the parent skin of sandwich panel;

Cure the entire repair region and examine the completed repair.

Bonded repair has been conducted on composite sandwich panels with one side skin and full-depth core penetrated damage. Experimental study are carried out to investigate the edgewise compressive behaviors of repaired panels and the influence of different repair parameters including repair materials (MTM vs. CYCOM), taper ratios (1/30 vs. 1/10) and repair techniques (scarf vs. step) are discussed. Experimental results indicate that the repair method presented in the paper can recover the 90% of static mechanical performance of damaged sandwich panels.
Based on the progressive damage analysis methodology, a 3D finite element model for the sandwich panel is established in the paper. Good agreements between calculation and experiment confirmed that the numerical model provides an effective analysis tool on the mechanical behavior prediction of repaired sandwich panels.
Quasi 3D joint models are established to study the stress distribution along the bond-line. Comparisons between different repaired specimens show: Different repair material could hardly decrease the loading-capacity of adhesive, but the critical location in adhesive transfers due to the stiffness mismatch between parent skin and repair plies;
